The correctness of this view is confirmed by what is said about the circumstances of his election. We are told (p. 73) that “the aforesaid Symon assumed the habitos a canon on the day of the Translation of S. Augustino (6 September), and on the same day, after ten years had elapsed, was elected Prior (Pastorl” As he resigned at Midsummer, 1297, thirty years from that date would bring us to Midsummer, 1267; but, as he was elected in September, we may allow him a further tenure of nine months, which is justified by the words et amplias, and consider him to have been elected Prior 6 September, 1266.

There is, however, another difficulty, namely, that the list of tenants in Book vll. was drawn up “ in 1295, and in the year since Symon de Ascellis became Prior the 31st’' (p. 282). May we decide that this statement was made from memory, and is therefore inaccurate?
